[2026-04-15]
CATEGORY: ARCHITECTURE
SERVICE: poc/indexer
TASK: hierarchical selection prompt design
SYMPTOM: Using the same selection prompt for routing (stage 1) and discrimination (stage 2+)
         conflates two different cognitive tasks.
ROOT_CAUSE: Stage 1 is recall-oriented routing (which section?). Stage 2+ is precision-
         oriented discrimination (which specific leaf?). A single prompt can't optimise
         for both simultaneously.
PREVENTED_BY: Use distinct prompt functions per stage. Stage 1 prompt: broad, tolerate
         false positives, framing is "route to sections". Stage 2+ prompt: narrow,
         precision-oriented, explicitly provides parent section context and prior reasoning
         so the model knows why the section was selected.
SOLUTION: Implemented as make_route_section_prompt() and make_discriminate_prompt().
DEAD_ENDS: None.

[2026-04-15]
CATEGORY: ARCHITECTURE
SERVICE: poc/indexer
TASK: two-stage vs walk-until-leaves
SYMPTOM: "Two-stage hierarchical selection" plan breaks for documents with 3+ level trees.
         Nodes like 1.11.L21 are at level 4; a two-stage walk stops at level 2 and never
         exposes them to the selection call.
ROOT_CAUSE: The plan assumed a two-level tree. The index has split-generated synthetic nodes
         at levels 3-4.
PREVENTED_BY: Implement "walk until all selected nodes are leaves" — recurse at each level
         until no non-leaves remain. This generalises to arbitrary depth at O(depth) calls.
         Two-stage is a special case of this for two-level trees.
SOLUTION: _hierarchical_select() implements the recursive loop. Confirmed working:
         1.11.L21 (level 4) correctly selected in eval.
DEAD_ENDS: Fixed two-stage walk — breaks silently for deep trees.

[2026-04-15]
CATEGORY: ARCHITECTURE
SERVICE: poc/indexer
TASK: discrimination prompt precision vs recall
SYMPTOM: Anchor-on-one discrimination (pick single best, add only if strictly absent)
         reduces noise (P1H: +14→+3) but drops recall on compound multi-section queries
         (P1H5: 3/3→1/3 expected nodes). P1H6 (dense siblings) requires anchoring;
         P1H5 (cross-section compound) requires inclusion. The two conflict.
ROOT_CAUSE: 300-char topic phrase descriptions are lossy. No retrieval prompt can recover
         information that was never indexed. Precision-oriented prompts amplify this loss
         by excluding nodes whose labels don't match the query vocabulary.
PREVENTED_BY: Prefer recall over precision at the discrimination stage. Stage 0 vocabulary
         fixes (corpus-grounded glossary, retrieval framing shift) are the correct tool for
         noise reduction — not discrimination tightening.
SOLUTION: Reverted to recall-oriented framing: "err inclusive; missing relevant content is
         worse than one extra section."
DEAD_ENDS: fix2 (anchor-on-one + "different facet"), fix3 (same + tighter wording),
         fix4 ("different part of the question"), fix5 (sub-question decomposition) —
         all traded recall for precision in ways the lossy index can't support.

