[2026-04-28]
CATEGORY: ARCHITECTURE
SERVICE: src/gateway
TASK: Sprint item Q — Rewrite before classify
INSIGHT: Moving rewrite() before classify() removes a hidden coupling: classify() no longer
         needs session history because the rewrite step handles all context-dependent fragments
         ("yes", "go ahead", "what about PE kit?") before the classifier ever sees them.
         The classifier always receives a self-contained, corpus-native question.
ROOT_CAUSE: The original order (classify → rewrite) forced history into classify() to handle
            short affirmative follow-ups. That was an architectural leak — two pipeline steps
            solving the same problem (context resolution) in different ways.
PREVENTED_BY: When a service step needs session history to understand the input, ask whether
              the problem is "context resolution" (belongs in rewrite) or "scope classification"
              (belongs in classify). If context resolution, move or extend rewrite instead of
              adding history to the classifier.

[2026-04-28]
CATEGORY: OPERATIONS
SERVICE: src/gateway
TASK: Deploy during sprint session
SYMPTOM: Running deploy.sh inside a session consumed ~50% of the context window in minutes.
         Docker push emits hundreds of "Layer X: Waiting" lines — one per layer per push
         attempt, repeated across parallel streams. Combined with IAM policy JSON dumps,
         a single deploy can produce 500+ lines of noise into the context window.
ROOT_CAUSE: deploy.sh output is captured verbatim into context. Docker push progress and
            gcloud IAM output are high-volume, low-information noise.
PREVENTED_BY: Always deploy at session end (after /wrap), never mid-session. If deploy must
              happen mid-session, pipe through: `bash deploy.sh 2>&1 | grep -E '(===|Done|Service|Error|Deploying|Revision)' `
              to suppress layer noise and IAM dumps. Never run deploy.sh unfiltered mid-session.

